<font color="#FF0000">TO DIXIE</font><br>
<tt>Thu Jul  3 11:42:27 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
TO DIXIE:<br>
As an assault helicopter pilot I had a front row seat in Vietnam and am familiar with the horrors of war. The fact that you were a woman or that you were enlisted or that you served in logistics does not detract from the honor due you. I served two tours in Nam and I never failed to respect the &quot;Rear echelon&quot; who provided my mail, food, and certainly my medical care when I was badly wounded.  I believe that I am joined by many survivors of intense combat in saluting you for you immeasurable effort and invite you to share the honor and pain due all warriors.<br>
I do extensive research on Post Traumatic Stress Disorders and am the author of &quot;Scars and Stripes, Forever.&quot;  I urge you to seek help at your nearest VA facility and file for a PTSD claim.  Interaction with fellow veterans is often helpful but professional care is sometimes a must.  You need not subordinate yourself to those who fought and died.  The very fact that you placed yourself in harms way makes you a member of everyone's team.  God Bless You and Welcome Home!
<p><code>-- eramon@edu.master.net  (Edward Ramon) </code><p>


